    {
      "id": "587e4dab8dd505260924460a5e9dc9b924e1c39a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 554,
        "name": "Vinayak",
        "email": "vinayakswami.hariharmath@seagate.com",
        "username": "vinayakh",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-02-26 12:30:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHello Christopher,\n\nfprintf() is the reason which can change the errno. However we have already saved the value in rc and we can use the same to report it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "645a2375e3534a821cc121a91517396c224714d2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 301,
        "name": "Dmitry Eremin",
        "email": "dmitry.eremin@intel.com",
        "username": "dmiter",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-02-26 18:49:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nActually errno will be read before call function fprintf() because of it's argument of this function. Therefore fprintf() cannot affect the output.\n\nI also don't see the real value from this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "1d22c4d0fbe386c1785881f1378f15ff743b1f50",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 554,
        "name": "Vinayak",
        "email": "vinayakswami.hariharmath@seagate.com",
        "username": "vinayakh",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-02-27 03:34:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHello Dimitry,\n\nThere is a small window of time between storing the error code into errno when the system call returns and printing of this value by program during which the errno can be changed for example any thread in execution in the same process may change it. That's the reason why we store the \"errno\" into \"rc\". So same \"rc\" should be used in fprintf.\n\nIn rare cases, fprintf can also set errno. So its safe to use stored value \"rc\" while reporting the error string in fprintf.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a2d553494410e6447d6bd3fcb18641ada414f089",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2016-02-29 21:03:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nActually, that is not accurate.  errno is explicitly a thread local variable.  It pretty much has to be, otherwise the entire standard C library error handling would be unsafe.  Your \"fix\" here would not fix that race condition either, only make it a little smaller.\n\nAdditionally, errno in these case is passed by value to printf, not passed by reference.  While errno can potentially change under printf, it has already been passed by value so there is no risk of that errno change modifying the output of the print statement.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "147a4a911943e5f35cd85e1d2c0f494b34a01e07",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 636,
        "name": "CORAL Checkpatch",
        "email": "hpdd-gerrit@intel.com",
        "username": "coral-checkpatch",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-05-25 17:14:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLooks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
